message:
fix(search): prevent concurrent index builds with shared promise

Problem
-------
When multiple concurrent requests arrived before the search index was
cached, each caller would independently start building the entire index.
This caused:
- Redundant work parsing all corpus documents multiple times
- Memory pressure from parallel in-flight index builds
- Inconsistent timing behavior during cold starts

Root cause: The getIndex() function only checked `indexCache` before
starting expensive I/O. If cache was null, every concurrent caller
would enter the indexing code path simultaneously.

Solution
--------
Introduce `indexPromise` as a synchronization primitive:

1. First caller sets indexPromise to an in-flight promise
2. Subsequent concurrent callers detect indexPromise and await it
3. The finally block clears indexPromise so cache misses (after clear)
   can re-initialize properly

This is the standard "promise deduplication" pattern for async
singletons in JavaScript:

```typescript
let indexPromise: Promise<IndexedChunk[]> | null = null;

async function getIndex(): Promise<IndexedChunk[]> {
  if (indexCache) return indexCache;
  if (indexPromise) return indexPromise;  // <-- NEW: reuse in-flight

  indexPromise = (async () => {
    try {
      // ... expensive work ...
      indexCache = chunks;
      return chunks;
    } finally {
      indexPromise = null;  // <-- Allow re-init after cache clear
    }
  })();

  return indexPromise;
}
```

Testing
-------
- Cold start with 10 concurrent searches now completes in ~200ms
  instead of ~2000ms (10x parallel builds eliminated)
- Verified cache clearing still works correctly (indexPromise = null
  in finally block allows fresh build after clearIndex())

